<p>As a physiatrist specializing in lower-limb biomechanics, I present the following <strong>podiatry orthotics fabrication method report</strong> and representative case outcome.</p><hr><h1>Podiatry Orthotics Fabrication Method Report</h1><h2>Functional Longitudinal–Transverse Arch Orthosis with Rearfoot and Cuboid Control</h2><h3>1. Biomechanical Rationale</h3><p>This custom foot orthotic system is designed to support:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Longitudinal arch</strong></p></li><li><p><strong>Transverse arch</strong></p></li><li><p>Rearfoot stabilization through dual talar support</p></li><li><p>Lateral column stabilization through cuboid support</p></li></ul><p>The design integrates principles from:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Merton Root</strong> – Coronal plane biomechanics and subtalar neutral concept</p></li><li><p><strong>Kevin Kirby</strong> – Tissue stress theory and subtalar joint axis deviation</p></li><li><p><strong>Howard Dananberg</strong> – Sagittal plane facilitation, ankle dorsiflexion, and first MTP extension</p></li></ul><p>The objective is to optimize ground reaction force (GRF) positioning relative to the subtalar joint axis, minimizing excessive pronation/supination moments while facilitating efficient sagittal plane progression.</p><hr><h2>2. Structural Design Characteristics</h2><h3>A. Longitudinal Arch Support (Kinematic Matching)</h3><p>Unlike static medial arch posting, this orthosis is fabricated to match the patient’s <strong>kinematic longitudinal arch contour</strong>, determined under semi-weightbearing alignment.</p><p>This reduces localized pressure concentration and distributes load evenly across the medial column.</p><hr><h3>B. Dual Rearfoot Support System&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: inherit;">- mimicking acetabulum pedis (cfunction&nbsp;</span></h3><h4>1. Sustentaculum Tali Support&nbsp;</h4><p>Provides medial talocalcaneal stabilization and limits excessive subtalar joint eversion.</p><h4>2. Talar Head Support</h4><p>Designed to mimic the functional containment of the <strong>acetabulum pedis</strong>, supporting the talar head and preventing medial–plantar displacement during stance phase.</p><p>Together, these components:</p><ul><li><p>Reduce subtalar joint overpronation</p></li><li><p>Shift GRF toward a zone of minimal pronation/supination moment</p></li><li><p>Decrease tibial internal rotation stress transmission proximally</p></li></ul><hr><h3>C. Cuboid Support Lift</h3><p>A lateral column lift is incorporated under the cuboid to:</p><ul><li><p>Mimic the stabilizing function of:</p><ul><li><p>Long and short plantar ligaments</p></li><li><p>Peroneus longus tendon</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Facilitate the midtarsal “locking mechanism”</p></li><li><p>Improve forefoot rigidity during terminal stance</p></li></ul><p>This enhances propulsion efficiency and reduces compensatory medial knee stress.</p><hr><h3>D. Transverse Arch Accommodation</h3><p>Forefoot contouring supports metatarsal alignment and assists in redistributing plantar pressures.</p><hr><h3>E. Sagittal Plane Facilitation</h3><p>Consistent with Dananberg’s model, the orthotic contour:</p><ul><li><p>Facilitates ankle dorsiflexion</p></li><li><p>Allows first metatarsophalangeal joint extension</p></li><li><p>Reduces compensatory midfoot collapse</p></li></ul><hr><h2>3. Fabrication Method</h2><ol><li><p><strong>Biomechanical Assessment</strong></p><ul><li><p>Resting Calcaneal Stance Position (RCSP)</p></li><li><p>Subtalar neutral palpation</p></li><li><p>Subtalar joint axis estimation</p></li><li><p>Limb length evaluation</p></li><li><p>Dynamic gait observation</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Casting/Scanning Position</strong></p><ul><li><p>Semi-weightbearing</p></li><li><p>Midtarsal joint pronated</p></li><li><p>Subtalar joint positioned near neutral</p></li><li><p>Forefoot to rearfoot relationship maintained</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Positive Model Modification</strong></p><ul><li><p>Medial arch sculpted to kinematic contour</p></li><li><p>Sustentaculum tali prominence reinforced</p></li><li><p>Talar head indentation contoured</p></li><li><p>Cuboid lift integrated</p></li><li><p>Balanced medial-lateral hardness</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Material Selection</strong></p><ul><li><p>Semi-rigid shell</p></li><li><p>Balanced bilateral contact hardness</p></li><li><p>Top cover adjusted for pressure distribution</p></li></ul></li></ol><hr><h1>Case Report</h1><h3>Patient Profile</h3><ul><li><p>28-year-old male</p></li><li><p>History of seronegative spondyloarthropathy</p></li><li><p>1-month history of left medial knee pain (VAS 5)</p></li><li><p>Pain aggravated by prolonged walking</p></li></ul><hr><h3>Clinical Findings</h3><ul><li><p>Leg length discrepancy: right longer than left by 10 mm</p></li><li><p>Bilateral rearfoot pronation on RCSP</p></li><li><p>Tenderness over left medial joint line</p></li><li><p>Ultrasound:</p><ul><li><p>Grade 1 medial collateral ligament (MCL) injury</p></li><li><p>Bony erosions</p></li><li><p>No active inflammation</p></li></ul></li></ul><p>Previous orthotic use:</p><ul><li><p>Medial arch support bilaterally</p></li><li><p>Asymmetrical hardness (left harder)</p></li><li><p>Persistent symptoms (VAS 4 after 1 month)</p></li></ul><hr><h2>Biomechanical Interpretation</h2><p>Excessive rearfoot pronation likely contributed to:</p><ul><li><p>Increased tibial internal rotation</p></li><li><p>Elevated medial knee joint stress</p></li><li><p>Increased strain across medial collateral ligament</p></li><li><p>Medial compartment load concentration</p></li></ul><p>The unbalanced insole hardness likely produced asymmetric force transmission.</p><hr><h2>Intervention</h2><p>Custom orthotics fabricated with:</p><ul><li><p>Kinematic longitudinal arch contour</p></li><li><p>Dual rearfoot support (sustentaculum tali + talar head)</p></li><li><p>Cuboid lift for lateral column stabilization</p></li><li><p>Balanced bilateral hardness</p></li><li><p>Functional correction of coronal plane alignment</p></li><li><p>Sagittal plane facilitation</p></li></ul><hr><h2>Outcome</h2><p>After transition to custom orthotics:</p><ul><li><p>Medial knee pain resolved</p></li><li><p>No recurrence of symptoms</p></li><li><p>Improved walking tolerance</p></li><li><p>No flare of underlying inflammatory disease</p></li></ul><hr><h1>Clinical Significance</h1><p>This case demonstrates:</p><ol><li><p>The importance of <strong>precise rearfoot control</strong>, not merely medial arch elevation</p></li><li><p>The role of <strong>subtalar joint axis optimization</strong> in reducing proximal joint stress</p></li><li><p>The necessity of <strong>balanced material hardness</strong> to prevent asymmetric load transfer</p></li><li><p>The value of integrating:</p><ul><li><p>Root’s coronal plane correction</p></li><li><p>Kirby’s tissue stress theory</p></li><li><p>Dananberg’s sagittal plane facilitation</p></li></ul></li></ol><p>Custom orthotics fabricated according to functional biomechanics rather than generic arch support can significantly reduce medial knee stress and prevent recurrence of ligamentous injury.</p><hr><p>If desired, I can also format this into:</p><ul><li><p>A journal-style case report</p></li><li><p>A clinic documentation template</p></li><li><p>An insurance/medical-legal report format</p></li><li><p>A presentation slide outline for academic teaching</p></li></ul>